{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum Hamming weight of the product of a constant (2023) and an arbitrary integer n. This is equivalent to finding the minimum number of ones in the binary representation of any multiple of 2023. This is a classic problem in number theory related to the order of 2 modulo the factors of the number.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "factorization_and_modular_analysis",
      "instructions": "Factorize 2023 into its prime components. Determine if 2023 is coprime to 2 (it is, as it is odd). Analyze the properties of the multiplicative order of 2 modulo 2023, or more specifically, find the smallest m such that 2^m ≡ 1 (mod 2023) or 2^m ≡ some value that allows for a low Hamming weight."
    },
    {
      "label": "hamming_weight_minimization_search",
      "instructions": "Investigate the minimum number of ones in the binary representation of multiples of 2023. Test if k(n)=1 is possible (requires 2023 to be a power of 2, which it isn't). Test if k(n)=2 is possible (requires 2023 to divide 2^a + 2^b for some a, b). This is equivalent to checking if 2^a ≡ -2^b (mod 2023), or 2^{a-b} ≡ -1 (mod 2023). Check if k(n)=3 is possible (requires 2023 to divide 2^a + 2^b + 2^c)."
    },
    {
      "label": "order_of_two_modulo_factors",
      "instructions": "Calculate the order of 2 modulo each prime factor of 2023. Specifically, find the order of 2 modulo 7 and modulo 17 (since 2023 = 7 * 17^2). Use these to determine the smallest k such that 2^k ≡ 1 (mod 2023) and check if there exists an integer m such that 2^m ≡ -1 (mod 2023), which would imply k(n)=2."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the results to determine the smallest possible number of ones. First, rule out k(n)=1. Second, check if k(n)=2 is possible by checking if -1 is in the cyclic subgroup generated by 2 modulo 2023 (i.e., if the order of 2 modulo 2023 is even and 2^(order/2) ≡ -1 mod 2023). If k(n)=2 is impossible, check if k(n)=3 is possible by checking if there exist a, b such that 2^a + 2^b ≡ 0 (mod 2023) is false, but 2^a + 2^b + 1 ≡ 0 (mod 2023) or similar combinations are true. The final answer is the smallest k found."
}
```

